Title: Meditations
Author: Marcus Aurelius
My Review: If I were rating this on the basis of historical coolness it would be 5 stars. However the act of actually reading this from cover to cover was a bit painful. I enjoyed the opening introduction by Hays, but I found the main text extremely repetitive and disjointed. Of course this makes sense because this was never intended to be published. I also found the philosophy to be a bit simple and not very rigorous. It's kinda just like reading a series of extremely similar mantras for 170 pages.... I'm Sorry Marcus I'm sure you were a great guy and all but your diary was not my cup of tea.

Title: The Catcher in the Rye
Author: J.D. Salinger
My Review:
Just as good as I remember. I know there are some people who despise this book, but I think it just comes down to whether or not you can sympathize/empathize with Holden.

Having dealt with depression around the same age as Holden, and having had similar self destructive thoughts as him I have a hard time getting through this book with dry eyes.That's not to say the book is overtly sad or depressing, in fact it's very funny at times.

I think a lot of people criticize Holden as a whiny annoying teenager, but that's kinda the whole point. He literally can't enjoy anything, and people who have suffered from depression can relate to that.

In my opinion the book is about Holden's battle with depression and how he learned to deal with it. I think the most important chapter is when he goes to meet Mr Antolini. He kind of gives Holden the right advice when he basically tells him to stop moralizing so much. At the end of the day that's Holden's problem he constantly judges and moralizes everyone and everything in the book and that's the driving force of his depression. It's not until the end when he is able to just enjoy watching Phoebe ride on the carousel that he actually learns this lesson.

I know this tends to be a love it or hate it type book, but I fricken love it to death. Still my favorite fiction book as of February 16 2022.

Title: Amusing Ourselves to Death: Public Discourse in the Age of Show Business
Author: Neil Postman
My Review:
One of the most condemning books ever written about modern technological culture.
Do you want to know:
-Why we elected a reality TV star as President?
-Why public discourse has become unfathomably absurd?
-Why mainstream news is so damaging?

This book answers all of these questions and more. However don't expect to walk away from this book with an optimistic attitude towards the future, but it is definitely worth the read if you are of the type that would like to be aware of our collective cultural demise.
